sec.p:
There are three one-dimensional irreducible representations of the group, denoted as
(A2)$$\begin{eqnarray}
1: && S = 1, \qquad T = 1,\\
\end{eqnarray}$$(A3)$$\begin{eqnarray}
1': && S = 1, \qquad T = e^{i4\pi/3}\equiv \omega^2,\\
\end{eqnarray}$$(A4)$$\begin{eqnarray}
1'':&& S = 1, \qquad T = e^{i2\pi/3}\equiv \omega.
\end{eqnarray}$$

It is easy to check that there is no two-dimensional irreducible representation of this group. The three-dimensional unitary representations of $T$ and $S$ are given by
(A5)$$\begin{eqnarray}
T =\left(\begin{array}{ccc}
1 & 0 & 0\\
0 & \omega^2 & 0 \\
0 & 0 & \omega \end{array}\right)\!,\qquad
S= \frac{1}{3}{\left(\begin{array}{ccc}
-1 & 2 & 2\\
2 & -1 & 2 \\
2 & 2 & -1\end{array}\right)},\label{AFbasis}
\end{eqnarray}$$
where $T$ has been chosen to be diagonal. The multiplication rules for the singlet and triplet representations corresponding to the above basis of two generators $T, S$ are given as
(A6)$$\begin{equation}
1\times1 = 1, \quad 1'\times1'' = 1,\quad 3\times3 = 3 + 3_A +1 + 1' + 1''.
\end{equation}$$

For triplets
(A7)$$\begin{equation}
a = (a_1, \ a_2, \ a_3), \qquad b=(b_1, \ b_2,\ b_3),
\end{equation}$$
one can write
(A8)$$\begin{eqnarray}
1 \equiv (ab) &=& (a_1b_1+a_2b_3+a_3b_2),\\
\end{eqnarray}$$(A9)$$\begin{eqnarray}
1' \equiv (ab)' &=& (a_3b_3+a_1b_2+a_2b_1),\\
\end{eqnarray}$$(A10)$$\begin{eqnarray}
1'' \equiv (ab)'' &=& (a_2b_2+a_1b_3+a_3b_1).
\end{eqnarray}$$

For the one-dimensional reps, it is easy to see these properties because $(\omega^2)^*=\omega$. For the 3-reps we can find a transformation $U$ that changes $3^*$ into $3$ or $3^*\sim3$ and vice versa. This is similar to the case of $SU(2)$ symmetry. Namely, $UTU^{-1}=T^*=T^2$ and $USU^{-1}=S^*=S$ for $T$ and $S$ given in Eq. (A5). We can see this in the $S_4$ group where all of $T$, $T^2$, and $S$ are in the same conjugate class; see the details in Refs. [104,105]. Hence, $U$ belongs to $S_4$ but not $A_4$, namely
(A14)$$\begin{equation}\label{eq_Utts}
U=TSTS^2=\left(
\begin{array}{ccc}
1 & 0 & 0 \\
0 & 0 & 1 \\
0 & 1 & 0 \\
\end{array}
\right)\!.
\end{equation}$$

